EXECUTIVE SUMMARY
The AEGIS HOUSING BASEMENT SYSTEM is a climate-resilient, blockchain-integrated housing protocol that places the basement as the true heart of the home.
This protocol fully open-sources the basement engineering (Passive Geothermal Energy Bank, thermal mass, geothermal loops, flood-resistant drainage, and all mathematical models) under MIT / Apache 2.0, while keeping upper-house architectural IP proprietary but cryptographically auditable.
Core Innovation: The basement is simultaneously the structural foundation, passive geothermal energy plant, energy storage system, and bright usable living space — delivering 60–70% energy savings with zero utility bills and zero maintenance.
Project Wallet: CzdBHjP7CkqRaYrxwoCxDpFhXU2B6akZ5rfFKQqo1NCj (Solana Mainnet)

1. ARCHITECTURAL DESIGN
Footprint: Trapezoidal — 20 ft front façade widening to 40 ft at rear × 33.3 ft depth
Height: 4 stories
Signature Feature: Inverted U-Shell Roof — Strong structural U-shaped corrugated marine-grade stainless steel shell that wraps over the top and down the sides (primary load-bearing and protective element)
Exterior:

Corrugated marine-grade stainless steel U-shell with subtle weathering
Triple-glazed low-E windows with thin black frames
Natural stone veneer on lower levels
Integrated tubular daylighting domes

Landscaping: Positive 2% grading with bioswale systems

2. PASSIVE GEOTHERMAL ENERGY BANK (100% OPEN SOURCE)
Depth: 3 meters (10 ft)
Earth Temperature: Stable 50–55 °F
Thermal Mass: 80–95 cubic yards of high-mass reinforced concrete
Geothermal Loops: 1,400 linear feet of 1" SDR-11 HDPE embedded during pour
Passive Capacity: 55,000 – 100,000 BTU/hr
Circulation Power: <100 W in shoulder seasons
Construction: Single mini-excavator (≈40 hours)
Fully Open Source:

All geothermal engineering
Fourier heat transfer models
Load calculations and tolerances
Construction sequences


